Document: Timer
Path: godot/classes/class_timer.rst
Summary: The Timer node is used to create timed events.

Inherits: Node < Object

The Timer node is used to create timed events. It emits a timeout() signal when the specified wait time has elapsed. This can be used for a variety of purposes, such as:

*   Implementing delays between actions.
*   Creating repeating events.
*   Controlling the timing of animations or game logic.

The Timer node has several properties that can be configured:

*   wait_time (float): The time in seconds to wait before emitting the timeout() signal.
*   one_shot (bool): If true, the timer will stop after emitting the timeout() signal once. If false, the timer will repeat.
*   autostart (bool): If true, the timer will start automatically when the scene is loaded.
*   editable (bool): If true, the timer can be edited in the editor.

The Timer node also has several methods that can be used to control its behavior:

*   start(): Starts the timer.
*   stop(): Stops the timer.
*   pause(): Pauses the timer.
*   unpause(): Unpauses the timer.
*   is_stopped(): Returns true if the timer is stopped, false otherwise.
*   is_paused(): Returns true if the timer is paused, false otherwise.

The Timer node emits the following signals:

*   timeout(): Emitted when the wait time has elapsed.
